The NBA Draft. A chance for change¶

Throughout all of sports, a draft is one of the most important moments of the year. It gives the worst teams of their respective league the chance to choose the best avaliable prospects to play for their respective francise. Instead of the player choosing where they want to play like in free agency, the organization chooses the players they believe has the best odds of helping their organization win, and then that player must play for that organization until they are allowed to enter free agency a couple of years later. The draft brings these organizations a choice, like what player we should draft, what schools have the best players and much more. In this project, I hope to uncover some of the mysteries of the draft, and try to find out what sort of player should be selected in next years NBA draft

The data frame above can be used to help an NBA scout to figure out what colleges might produce quality players. In the NBA, the longer a player is on the court, the better the player in most cases. This is true with all sports but especially in the NBA where there are only five players on the court at a time. There is a small problem with using this method to try to figure out what college a team should draft from. This data frame uses the average minutes played for each college, which can be suseptiable to outliers and small data sets. For example, it looks like it would be a good idea to draft a player from Lehigh, the only problem is that there has been only one player drafted in school history, CJ McCollum. Since CJ has been the only player drafted from Lehigh, it could make this data frame very hard to use for any form of analysis since it can be swayed by colleges that have only had a couple of players drafted, as compared to bigger schools such as UNC which has had over 40 players drafted since 1989.

From this data exploration, we see an interesting pattern. The drop in average points per game gets smaller and smaller as we get to lower draft positions. This makes sense because a player can't score lower than zero points in a basketball game, so the graph trends towards that limit. This can also be helpful in trying to figure out if a team should trade up in the draft for a better pick, what pick should they aim for. Say a team has the 20th pick, they are going to get similar points from any player between pick 10-20. It's only when we get above pick 10 do we start to see a sizable change in points per game. So if I was a general manager in the NBA, I would be trying to trade for a top 10 pick as that would see a sizable increase in average production.

This graph gives us another perspective on which draft positions and which ones might be useful. All of the early picks have very wide ranges with a small amount of data gathered around the mean. These early draft picks have a small chance to have incredible scoring averages, but also the same change of having a terrible scoring average as well. It isn't until you get to around pick 30 where you shart to see more of the data around the mean. These picks don't have as much upside as the earlier picks, but there is less of a change they will result in a bust. This is something to consider if you are a general manager for an NBA team.

Win Shares Analysis¶

The next Part of my Analysis will look at draft positions and their corresponding win shares. Win shares is an advanced NBA stats that attempts to quantify how much a player contributes to a teams win. If a player has one win share, they contributed to exactally one win that season. For more Info, Win Shares

For a general manager who is drafting a player, it can be helpful to see how many wins a draft position would contribute each year. This could be super helpful as if a team missed the playoffs last year by 3 wins, they would hopefully only need to draft a position that has a win share per season average of over 3 to get into the playoffs. The team might have the 20th pick in the draft, which would not be enough of an increase in games to make the playoffs the next year, so they might want to consider trading up to get a higher pick.

The Draft By Player Statistics Final Thoughts¶

After looking at a couple of measurements of player success in the NBA, we found some interesting trends. The first is that there appears to be a polynomial relationship between draft position and player success. This makes sense though, as a player can't have a statistic less than zero. For example, a player can't score less than zero points in a game. Also another factor is that there are only 60 players drafted each year, so the graphs do end without going to zero exactally. But this does bring up an interesting question with drafting and if you should trade up in the draft. It normally would not make sense to trade up from the 20th draft position to the 19th position because the player will only be marginally better on average, and the picks and players you might have to give up would not be worth it. The second interesting trend that I saw was that the third pick was always better than the second pick in terms of statistics. This is really interesting at normally you would think the second pick would be a lot better than the third pick since the graph follows a polynomial relationship, but this is not the case. This might have to do with the nature of the draft. It is hard to pick out players from their time in college and overseas and translate that into success in the NBA. That is why drafting is so hard and the best player in the draft in not always picked first. So what should a general manager do. The small problem we have with the current analysis is that we are only looking at players statistics after they have been drafted, not before. There was no data on a players college statistics or statistics from their previous league (if they played overseas for example). Also another problem we have is we are not looking at the teams these players are being drafted to. Where a player is drafted to is a big factor into their success. For example, James Wiseman was drafted to the Warriors second overall in 2020, but has not gotten a lot of playing time even though he was a second overall pick. This is because the warriors already have a stacked roster with players like Steph Curry, Klay Thompson, and Draymond Green, so there is not a lot of playing time for Wiseman to get on the floor. This has hampered his career statistics and impact on the court but if Wiseman was drafted to a team like the Houston Rockets, who have been one of the worst teams since he was drafted, he might have better career statistics.

In [31]:
def wasPicked(x, name, year):
    temp_df = college_stats[college_stats['player_name'] == name]
    max_year = temp_df['year'].max()
    if max_year == year:
        if x == x:
            return True
        return False
    return False

In [40]:
def wasPicked2(x, name, year):
    temp_df = was_drafted[was_drafted['player_name'] == name]
    max_year = temp_df['year'].max()
    if max_year == year:
        if x == x:
            return True
        return False
    return False

So after looking at the summary, there appears to be a small relationship between points per game in college and draft position. this might have to do with a lot of factors such as what school they play at. For example, they might play at a non power five conference school (such as Lehigh), average 30 points but get drafted 35th while a player at kansas can average 20 and be a top 5 pick. This is because we aren't taking into account variables such as strength of schedule and teammates that could dictate this average. Another factor for a player being drafted is the year they are in college. It is more impressive for a Freshman to average 20 points than a senior to average 20 points. This is why we see the Freshman average pick be lower than all of the other years for the same number of points.

Conclusion¶

After going through all of the data, we have found some interesting trends with NBA players and the draft. The first is that there is a polynomial relationship between a draft pick and their average production. it is not a linear decrease with each pick. This might be because their are only five players on the court at a time so lower drafted players don't get that much playing time, or something else entiely. We also found out that based on a college players statistics in college, we can determine what players are going to be drafted pretty accurately. This can be super helpful for college players who want to go to the nba to figure out what typs of production they need in college to get to the next level. This could also be helpful for NBA general managers to see what types of players are NBA ready. The last bit of knowledge we gained is that we can not determine an NBA players impact based on their college statistics. There are too many other factors that are in play that aren't captured by statistics that determine if a player will be productive in the NBA. This is why even with all of this information avaliable to general managers, we still have players who are busts. Sometimes you just need to get a little lucky in the draft to turn your franchise around.
